steps.instruction:
Produce two artifacts (epics + work_breakdown) in a single JSON object. Group user stories into epics, then break every story into implementation tasks following the feature template pattern (db_migration, backend, frontend, tests, e2e, code_review).

OUTPUT FORMAT: Return ONLY a JSON object directly in `result` (no JSON-string wrapping, no `final_answer` envelope, no Markdown). Object MUST have these top-level keys:

{
  "epics": [
    {"epic_id": "E-01", "name": "...", "description": "...", "user_stories": ["US-001", ...], "dependencies": ["E-..."], "estimated_total_effort": "S|M|L|XL", "priority_order": 1}
  ],
  "work_breakdown": {
    "tasks": [
      {"task_id": "T-001", "story_id": "US-001", "epic_id": "E-01", "agent": "coder|tester|reviewer", "dependencies": ["T-..."], "estimated_effort": "S|M|L"}
    ]
  }
}

Cap epics at 8, tasks at 60. Order epics by dependency / value / risk.

Plan Sprint 0 (foundation work) plus all feature sprints. Each feature sprint delivers a demonstrable increment, balanced frontend/backend, 80% capacity for buffer, includes review + testing.

OUTPUT FORMAT: Return ONLY a JSON object directly in `result` (no JSON-string wrapping, no `final_answer` envelope, no Markdown). Object MUST have these top-level keys:

{
  "sprint_0_plan": {
    "tasks": [
      {"task_id": "S0-T-01", "name": "...", "category": "repo|ci|docker|scaffold|design|db|tests|staging|docs", "agent": "coder|tester|reviewer|writer", "estimated_effort": "S|M|L"}
    ],
    "order": ["S0-T-01", "S0-T-02", "..."]
  },
  "sprint_plans": [
    {
      "sprint_id": "S1",
      "name": "...",
      "goal": "...",
      "tasks": [
        {"task_id": "T-001", "story_id": "US-001", "agent": "coder|tester|reviewer", "estimated_effort": "S|M|L"}
      ],
      "deliverable": "<demonstrable increment>"
    }
  ]
}

Cap sprint_0_plan.tasks at 15. Cap sprint_plans at 6 sprints, each with up to 12 tasks.

Z1 Tier 5 (A6) — failure premortem. Imagine it is exactly one year from today and the product has failed. Write THREE plausible obituaries — one per kind: `technical`, `market`, `founder`. For EACH, give a short obituary paragraph, a plausibility score (integer 1-5, where 5 = highly plausible), a one-sentence root cause, and (optionally) the id of an existing monitoring rule that would catch this failure mode (or null if none yet exists).

OUTPUT FORMAT: write `mission_{mission_id}/premortem.md` containing both human-readable bullets AND a fenced ```json block with this STRICT envelope:

```json
{
  "_schema_version": "1",
  "scenarios": [
    {"kind": "technical", "obituary": "...", "plausibility": 1-5, "cause": "...", "mapped_monitoring_rule": "<rule_id|null>"},
    {"kind": "market",    "obituary": "...", "plausibility": 1-5, "cause": "...", "mapped_monitoring_rule": "<rule_id|null>"},
    {"kind": "founder",   "obituary": "...", "plausibility": 1-5, "cause": "...", "mapped_monitoring_rule": "<rule_id|null>"}
  ]
}
```

Founder-mode obituaries are the most commonly missed in startup post-mortems — `founder loses interest in 4 weeks` is the most common cause of silent abandonment; surface it explicitly. Mechanical post-hook `verify_premortem_shape` rejects envelopes missing any kind, with <3 scenarios, or with plausibility outside [1,5].

Set up database client/ORM with connection pooling and configuration. Set up migration system with initial migration matching database_schema. Create seed data script with development data based on user_personas and business_rules. Verify migrations run forward and backward. Verify seed script populates data correctly.

AFTER the setup work is done, RETURN a JSON object directly in `result` (no envelope, no markdown, no "Wrote ..." summary):

{
  "db_client": {
    "client_path": "<path to db client/ORM module>",
    "connection_verified": true,
    "orm": "<library + version>",
    "pool_config": "<short description>"
  },
  "migration_system": {
    "tool": "<alembic|prisma|drizzle|...>",
    "initial_migration": "<path or id of the first migration>",
    "forward_verified": true,
    "backward_verified": true
  },
  "seed_script": {
    "script_path": "<path to seed script>",
    "data_summary": "<one line: what was seeded>",
    "populates_verified": true
  }
}

Set boolean fields to true ONLY when actually verified. If a verification couldn't run (tool unavailable), still emit the field as false with a `notes` sibling explaining why.

Set up test infrastructure for both backend and frontend. Backend: test framework (Jest/Vitest/pytest), test database config, test utilities (factories, fixtures, mocking), coverage reporting. Frontend: component testing (React Testing Library/Vue Test Utils), MSW or equivalent for API mocking, coverage reporting. Write at least one example test for each side and run it to verify the setup works.

AFTER the setup work is done, RETURN a JSON object directly in `result` (no envelope, no markdown, no "Wrote ..." summary):

{
  "backend_test_config": {
    "framework": "<pytest|jest|vitest>",
    "config_file": "<path to test config>",
    "example_test_passes": true,
    "coverage_tool": "<coverage|pytest-cov|c8>",
    "notes": "<one line: anything skipped or deferred>"
  },
  "frontend_test_config": {
    "framework": "<vitest|jest|...>",
    "config_file": "<path to test config>",
    "example_test_passes": true,
    "coverage_tool": "<c8|nyc|vitest coverage>",
    "notes": "<one line: anything skipped or deferred>"
  }
}

Set `example_test_passes` to true ONLY when the example test actually ran and exited 0. If the test couldn't run (tool unavailable, install failed), emit false and explain in notes.

Set up CI pipeline (GitHub Actions / GitLab CI / etc.): lint, type check, unit tests, integration tests, build, security scan. Set up CD pipeline for staging (auto-deploy on merge to develop) and production (deploy on tag/release). Configure dependency caching + coverage reporting.

AFTER the setup work is done, RETURN a JSON object directly in `result` (no envelope, no markdown, no "Wrote ..." summary):

{
  "ci_config": {
    "provider": "<github_actions|gitlab_ci|circleci|...>",
    "config_file": "<path to workflow file>",
    "stages": ["lint", "type_check", "unit_tests", "integration_tests", "build", "security_scan"],
    "caching": true,
    "coverage_uploaded": true
  },
  "cd_staging_config": {
    "trigger": "merge_to_develop",
    "config": "<path to staging deploy workflow>",
    "environment": "staging"
  },
  "cd_production_config": {
    "trigger": "tag_or_release",
    "config": "<path to production deploy workflow>",
    "environment": "production",
    "approval_gate": true
  }
}

If actual workflow files were written, set the boolean/path fields accordingly. If shell/write tools are unavailable in this run, still emit the object with planned values + add a `notes` sibling explaining what couldn't be executed.
